Common Injuries <br>
<br>

1. Burns: <br>
   First-Degree Burns: <br>

Symptoms: Redness, minor swelling, pain. <br>
Basic Treatment: <br>
Cool water compress or immerse the affected area in cool water for 10-15 minutes.
Apply an over-the-counter burn cream or aloe vera gel to soothe the skin.  <br>
Cover the burn with a sterile, non-adhesive bandage or gauze. <br>
Seek medical attention if the burn covers a large area, is on the face, hands, feet, or genitals, or if it appears infected. <br>

Second-Degree Burns: <br>
Symptoms: Blistering, severe pain, redness, swelling. <br>
Basic Treatment: <br>
Cool water compress or immerse the affected area in cool water for 10-15 minutes. <br>
Do not break blisters; leave them intact to reduce the risk of infection. <br>
Apply antibiotic ointment to the affected area and cover with a sterile, non-adhesive bandage. <br>
Elevate the burned area to reduce swelling. <br>
Seek medical attention for proper wound care and to prevent complications like infection. <br>

Third-Degree Burns: <br>

Symptoms: Charred or white skin, numbness (due to nerve damage), leathery texture. <br>
Basic Treatment: <br>
Immediate Medical Attention Required: Call emergency services or go to the nearest emergency room. <br>
Do not attempt to treat third-degree burns at home; they require professional medical care. <br>
Keep the affected person warm and elevate the burned area if possible. <br>
Cover the burn with a clean, dry cloth or sterile bandage, but do not apply any ointments or creams. <br>
Monitor the person for signs of shock and provide comfort and reassurance until medical help arrives. <br>

2. Fractures: <br>
   - Symptoms: Pain, swelling, deformity, inability to bear weight or move the injured area. <br>
   - Basic Treatment: Immobilization of the affected limb using a splint or cast, elevation, ice packs,  <br>and over-the-counter pain relievers. Seek medical attention for proper diagnosis and treatment. <br>



3. Sprains and Strains: <br>
     
Sprains: <br>
Symptoms: Pain, swelling, bruising, instability of the affected joint. <br>
Basic Treatment: <br>
Rest the injured joint and avoid putting weight on it. <br>
Apply ice packs to reduce swelling and pain (20 minutes on, 20 minutes off). <br>
Compression bandages can help reduce swelling and provide support. <br>
Elevate the injured limb above the heart if possible. <br>
Over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen or acetaminophen can help manage pain. <br>
Gradually reintroduce movement with gentle stretching and range-of-motion exercises. <br>
Severe sprains may require medical evaluation and physical therapy. <br>

Strains: <br>
Symptoms: Pain, swelling, muscle weakness, limited range of motion. <br>
Basic Treatment: <br>
Rest the affected muscle and avoid activities that cause pain. <br>
Apply ice packs to reduce swelling and pain (20 minutes on, 20 minutes off). <br>
Compression bandages can help reduce swelling and provide support. <br>
Elevate the injured limb above the heart if possible. <br>
Over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen or acetaminophen can help manage pain. <br>
Gentle stretching and strengthening exercises may be recommended once the acute pain subsides. <br>
Severe strains may require medical evaluation and physical therapy. <br>

4. Bruises: <br>
   - Symptoms: Discoloration of the skin (blue, purple, or black), tenderness. <br>
   - Basic Treatment: Ice packs applied intermittently for the first 24-48 hours to reduce swelling and pain, <br>rest, elevation, over-the-counter pain relievers. <br>

5. Cuts and Lacerations: <br>
   - Symptoms: Bleeding, pain, visible wound. <br>
   - Basic Treatment: Clean the wound with soap and water, apply direct pressure to stop bleeding, <br>cover with sterile bandages, seek medical attention for deep or jagged cuts that may require stitches. <br>

6. Concussions: <br>
    
Mild Concussions: <br>
Symptoms: Headache, dizziness, confusion, nausea, sensitivity to light or noise, memory problems. <br>
Basic Treatment: <br>
Rest (both physical and mental), avoiding activities that could worsen symptoms (such as screen time). <br>
Over-the-counter pain relievers like acetaminophen or ibuprofen can help manage headaches. <br>
Avoid alcohol, strenuous physical activity, and activities that require concentration or mental exertion. <br>
Gradually reintroduce activities once symptoms improve, but stop immediately if symptoms return. <br>
Medical evaluation is recommended to monitor for complications and ensure proper recovery. <br>

Moderate to Severe Concussions: <br>
Symptoms: Persistent or worsening headache, repeated vomiting, loss of consciousness, seizures, <br> weakness or numbness in limbs, difficulty waking up, slurred speech. <br>
Basic Treatment: <br>
Immediate Medical Attention Required: Call emergency services or go to the nearest emergency room. <br>
Follow emergency medical protocols for head injury management, which may include imaging tests (CT scan, MRI) and observation. <br>
Hospitalization may be necessary for close monitoring and management of complications. <br>
Follow-up care with a healthcare provider is essential for ongoing evaluation and management of symptoms. <br>
